-- AngloGold, Standard Bank: South Africa Stocks Preview
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-11-11T07:53:40Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-11/anglogold-imperial-standard-bank-may-move-south-african-equity-preview.html
(Corrects currency of earnings in AngloGold Ashanti.)  The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in South Africa.
Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names and prices
are from the last close.  South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index  lost 144.31,
or 0.5 percent, to 31,517.83 at the close in Johannesburg.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ): The mining company said
shipments from Collahuasi in Chile aren’t being affected by a
strike. Shares in Anglo, which makes up about 10 percent of
South Africa’s benchmark stock index, fell 3.38 rand, or 1
percent, to 327.60 rand.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ): The world’s third-biggest
producer of the precious metal posted net income of 443 million
rand ($64.4 million) for its third quarter, compared with a loss
of 1.36 billion rand during the previous three months. The
company also said full-year output is expected to be at the
lower end of its guidance. Shares in the company fell for the
first day in five, retreating 23 cents, or less than 0.1
percent, to 349.87 rand.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ): Copper surged to a record $8,945
a metric ton on the London Metal Exchange. Shares in BHP, the
world’s largest mining company, fell 6.70 rand, or 2.5 percent,
to 265.60 rand.  Imperial Holdings Ltd.  (IPL SJ): South Africa’s largest
auto dealer expects earnings per share excluding one-time items
for the six months through December to be as much as 45 percent
higher than a year earlier. Shares in the company gained 2.69
rand, or 2.2 percent, to 124 rand.  Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ): Oil rose for a second day, climbing as
much as 0.6 percent to $88.35 a barrel in electronic trading in
New York. Stock of Sasol, the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, rose 35 cents, or 0.1 percent, to 337.60 rand.  Standard Bank Group Ltd.  (SBK SJ): The lender faces a labor
court order from bank trade union Sasbo, which is opposing its
attempts to fire about 1,600 workers at its South African
operations. Shares in Standard Bank declined 87 cents, or 0.8
percent, to 105.05 rand.  Sun International Ltd.  (SUI SJ): The hotel and casino
operator plans to fund a 2.16 billion rand expansion out of its
cash resources and borrowings. Shares in Sun rose 50 cents, or
0.5 percent, to 103.50 rand.  Shares or American depositary receipts of the following
South African companies closed as follows:  Anglo American Plc (AAUKY US) rose 2.9 percent to $23.93.
AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (AU US) gained 4.9 percent to $51.21. BHP
Billiton Ltd. (BBL US) rose 0.5 percent to $78.01. DRDGold Ltd.
(DROOY US) rallied 3.9 percent to $5.28. Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI
US) climbed 5.4 percent to $17.82. Harmony Gold Mining Co. (HMY
US) rose 3.2 percent to $12.41. Impala Platinum Holdings Co.
(IMPUY US) advanced 2.9 percent to $31.39. Sappi Ltd. (SPP US)
climbed 3.8 percent to $5.50. Sasol Ltd. (SSL US) gained 1.4
percent to $49.08. Telkom South Africa Ltd. (TLKGY US) slid 1.8
percent to $20.90.  To contact the reporters on this story:
